European inflation slipped in food
Accelerating inflation in the euro area is primarily due to rapid growth in the price of food products.
The price increase in the month of November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
The official forecasts only gave like probable a 3 percent - announced the Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the North American, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, together with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, they would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB finds itself in trap 22: &quot;you have to negotiate&quot; on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
The inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, broke the record of twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of skyrocketing food and energy prices.
Forward prices of wheat increased by 88 percent and the price of soybeans reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, with black gold reaching almost $ 100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while for 2009 it will already decrease to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent in the next 3 or 4 months, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup foresees a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Young Democratic Alliance increased significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while Gallup never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of the socialists.
The difference in the case of the safe voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters - would mean a support of more than two thirds (71 percent) compared to the support of a fifth for the Socialists ( 20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the limit necessary to have a parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low point - it has never been so high, 41 percent of those who judged the country&#39;s economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe that the situation it&#39;s pretty bad.
Families, after the more hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about the change in their own economic situation.
With regard to next year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate and only a tenth expect an improvement.
In the month of December, 71 percent of those consulted, a figure higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the Prime Minister performs his duties badly rather than well.
13 percent of those consulted trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány a lot, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of those consulted.
54 percent of the population do not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced with the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the riots in October last year, 35 percent estimated that it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, currently this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority ( 33 percent) believe that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of those surveyed to the question on participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said that they are likely to participate.
By way of comparison, in &quot;a general election to be held this Sunday&quot; only 55 percent of the population would surely participate and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters, there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service and 84 percent of the hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of study fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs gold trading triangle maintained the average price level increase of 16 percent, with the difference that this year the VAT was not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year the usual Christmas basket of the Napi newspaper also increased by an average of 16 percent in the Budaörs golden commercial triangle, but all hypermarkets grew well above one thousand HUF.
As in December of last year prices had already &quot;skyrocketed&quot; in food supermarkets, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is evidently frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below HUF 9,000, today they cannot buy even for 10,000.
Napi&#39;s basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of 10,000 HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003 that basket cost HUF 6,800.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a strong increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the Coca-Cola with the two-liter redeemable bottle was less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even at the price of the bottle, was only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan&#39;s basket it was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year&#39;s Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18 percent the prices listed in Napi&#39;s basket.
Comparing the values of the most expensive basket last year with that of the cheapest basket this year, the difference was 12 percent, while the growth between the cheapest last year and the most expensive this year it has been 21 percent.
Average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so that during Christmas last year the VAT increased in prices.
It was precisely this process that destroyed the trade, the supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to apply for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the merchant poorly plans the speed of a product&#39;s circulation, he may lose a significant profit on the margin that matches the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of Napi&#39;s basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was 1,720 HUF higher than the value registered in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price so far has been HUF 1630 more than last year and the cheapest also increased to HUF 1284.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer items grew more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Statistical Office: this office, in the case of some staple foods, registered a price increase of more than 30 percent in the 12-month interval.
So for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to Napi&#39;s basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, since in the price of this product, which was already quite expensive last year compared to the base, it was registered, in the worst case, only 10 percent price increase.
By all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic price increase even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the golden commercial triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our collected experiences, the majority of consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy large quantities of all the products, taking preserved food by pallets.
In the morning of Wednesday, in the three stores large lines formed in front of the checkouts because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country the sales volumes are lower, numerous multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the income falls below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of household appliances.
In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year there have been several thousand infections in hospitals, caused in the first place by the improper application of antibiotics.
Hygiene circumstances prevailing in hospitals, overcrowded beds and overload of staff do not favor infection control - says the doctor-head of department of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals, savings are even made with disinfectants.
Not long ago an infection with MRSA was diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of bacteria resistant to antibiotics was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly after had to return to the hospital as a result of infection with MRSA and since then it has not been possible to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body. .
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, physician-department head of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that hospitals have surely registered this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents, there is no information on the rest.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, that is, Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of human beings carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any illness.
SA infections (eg, sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once antibiotics are overly or improperly applied, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become highly antibiotic resistant bacteria and spread rapidly under inappropriate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, for example wound infections or septicemia in the first place in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with a weakened organism, in the elderly or in people of little weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are common in hospitals.
Infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
&quot;These patients are isolated, the nursing staff treat them in rubber gloves and a mask and there are adequate antibiotics for their treatment&quot; - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously screened for the presence of MRSA in their bodies, but even then infection cannot be prevented in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate those with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This fact is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So that most cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the doctor-head of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict mandates for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
It is necessary to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance against drugs, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of ambulatory patients or in basic care - stated Karolina Böröcz.
You save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from patient to patient through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however, in this sense too, considerable shortcomings are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
What&#39;s more, hospital wards are often overcrowded, beds are often too close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with less favorable economic conditions, disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability of infection.
In Karolina Böröcz&#39;s opinion, where appropriate prevention measures are followed, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treating MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, which is why it is being fought in all countries.
In England for example there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program appears to be successful, based on the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections that are due to these pathogens.
