400 million euros more for infrastructures
The Hungarian Minister of Finance János Veres and the Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements for a total value of 400 million euros on Friday in Budapest to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructures , as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of 300 million euros to finance in the Hungarian budget transport and environmental protection projects, which will be made from the subsidy of cohesion funds, of which The parties had previously signed a credit agreement for a value of 100 million, the contract that they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The loan agreement of 150 million euros is also used to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of 300 million euros for this objective of Hungary, on the use of the remaining 150 million euros the decision will be taken later, when extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the conversations they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
An agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalizes with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will return to discuss the issue of whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this could take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth € 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is adjusted to the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a commission for keeping the loan at the disposal of the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian property market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that previously little mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and by whom are they buying on the even cheaper EU market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian Re / Max division.
The preferred target for property acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments on the ski slopes and villas on the beaches.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches of Albena, the &quot;Costa Dorada&quot;, the &quot;Costa del Sol&quot;, the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re / Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central part of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of property developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
In the same way, the capital Sofia may be attractive, the commercial and office spaces promise a quick return on investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, thus being able to be a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example around Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also making an effort to change their life and way of living.
Most of the clients are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present and traditionally there are many Russian clients on the beaches of the Black Sea and in ski paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re / Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They demand good communication and access, and for them the proximity of a big city, shops and generally a local doctor is important.
The second category is the buyers of villas (Bulgaria in December was included in the top 10 holiday destinations for Germans).
The third group is real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of the capital&#39;s real estate is constantly growing, since the demand is increasing.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest property prices in the European Union, in the last five years these have suffered an annual increase of 21 percent
The increase in property prices considerably exceeds the growth of wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian six percent
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration, negotiations will continue at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Road Map that provides for efforts after the emission reduction period, established in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Lively discussions on the subject are now taking place between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that for the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the situation in 1990, until 2020 the emission of gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent. responsible for the greenhouse effect.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological help to countries that need it.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, foreseen in the Kyoto Protocol, will be directed by a board of directors composed of 16 members, probably within the Global Fund for the Environment of the UN (GEF) - writes the &quot;Piac és Profit&quot;.
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU&#39;s efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister declared that the EU is committed to reducing its gas emissions by 20 percent by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the 1990 level, responsible for the greenhouse effect, regardless of whether or not the &quot;post-2012 agreement&quot; will be signed and is willing to commit to decreasing even 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the Kyoto Protocol of 1997 pledged to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states pledged to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary&#39;s commitment is to reduce the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with - states the press release from the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali, since within two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this In this case, the reduction commitments assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which was noted in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN international scientific association that deals with the climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2o C in the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: the special units deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - reported the BBC.
These recordings made by mini-cameras mounted on the helmets are monitored at the Kandahar General Operations Corps, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and their &quot;channel&quot; has already been seen by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of &quot;defense headquarters&quot; and publishes videos both of actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the forces Multinationals in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to introduce the public to the true objective of the British army&#39;s presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television recruiting spots - defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being of military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear on the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in &quot;official&quot; propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without presenting, however, the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in actual operations have been uploaded to the Internet and from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British Army is only recently seizing this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different way of recruiting with the free downloadable shooting video games called America&#39;s Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers.
