The party is not always written in red numbers
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and it has already become a general practice that around the holidays - which will be less next year - the working hours are reorganized.
Even in the EU or North America the holidays are not unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holiday, state holiday and public holidays.
The festive days are mainly related to religious festivals and historical events.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, as well as the first day of the new year is a holiday - the latter especially so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven parties written in red on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the 1848 revolution and on October 23, commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the State, on May 1 the labor festival, on November 1 and 2 we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, in our country Easter, Pentecost and Christmas are two-day holidays.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays seldom coincide with a weekend, so there is often a bridge when there is only one working day before or after the holiday.
In exchange for the long weekends like this, during the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the minister of labor that regulates in its specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or following the party.
This legal norm is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
On the other hand, it is not mandatory for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work uninterruptedly even during festive days.
This year the work order may only be altered around the end of the year holidays: as of December 24, life in the country practically stops, since according to experiences, most people &quot;bridge&quot; during the holidays. days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their vacations during these days.
Next year several of our parties will coincide with the middle or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in the working hours than this year.
First, the agenda around the work party will be modified so that later, for four successive days, the workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2, will be a holiday.
The other change is related to the party on October 23: on Saturday, October 18, we will have to work instead of Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year during the end of the year party you will be able to rest, since as of December 24 there will be no work almost anywhere, not even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six little deterrents to embitter the lives of your colleagues
Emails that we forget to send, audible messages that we never receive, innocent lies that are passed to us without realizing it: they are all part of our &quot;daily Folklore at work.&quot;
You have to decide whether to adapt to small annoyances or consciously avoid confusing situations that can irritate others.
Tips.
$ excuse me, I forgot to let you know that they have looked for you from the marketing department &quot;- says one of your colleagues.&quot;
That&#39;s why you didn&#39;t go on a date?
In the best of cases, he is sorry and tries to fix the matter, maybe he calls the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to deliver the message (this is the less common solution).
Most of the time the matter is resolved with an apology.
Before proceeding to embarrassing explanations, it is worth meditating on the things with which you can embitter the lives of your colleagues and consciously strive to avoid them.
Do you borrow something that is not yours?
There is nothing more irritating than when you want to take a document, an office supply or your phone and you cannot find them.
Do you remember that yesterday you put the stapler on the table, but by this morning it disappeared?
Do you find your pen lost on the table of one of your colleagues?
Don&#39;t take anything away from your colleagues without asking, because they will rightly be mad at you for stealing their things.
Do not take envelopes or post-its from the office because they can be unpleasant when you need them immediately and they sell out before the time.
Do you gossip about the private lives of your colleagues?
There is no good solution to stop rumors that are already running.
Who, what is he doing and with whom?
Where and why?
Do not pass the information (guesses) you have about the private lives of your colleagues to everyone!
Don&#39;t abuse your colleague&#39;s trust when he shares his most intimate secrets with you!
Bury in yourself what you have heard and do not gossip about your colleague in his absence, even if others know about him.
Are you going on sick leave unjustifiably?
When you call the office on the phone and say that you are sick and your head hurts unbearably, you feel bad or good, you feel that you prefer to rest that day; think about how others should do your job, your unpostponable tasks, your work by term.
Don&#39;t bother your colleague!
If you already know in advance that the next day you will not go to the office or something may happen to you, so you will have to stay at home, let them know, so that your colleagues or your boss do not have to confront your absence the next day.
Humming, giggling, phone calls
Are you involved in your work, but the giggles of your colleagues draw you out of it?
Have you unintentionally heard a phone conversation that it would have been better not to listen to?
Do not disturb your colleagues with your humming, singing, loud conversations (except when you do them above their head), kicking, constant profanity, expressing your discontent out loud.
All of these can be annoying, even if you&#39;re not digging into a project right now (writing, planning, organizing).
Do you blame others for a mistake?
Don&#39;t blame others if you didn&#39;t finish something on time, forgot to send an important letter or message!
Do not refer to the chaos that may eventually reign in the office, or to the noise that your colleagues make!
You must recognize if you have made a mistake that harms others and you must repair the fault!
Ask how you can repair your fault!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Jogging and slippers - very comfortable habit for the house, but not suitable for the office!
Don&#39;t wear a comfortable jogging suit even if your occupation allows it!
Do not be unkempt, respect yourself and your colleagues by wearing everyday, elegant and beautiful clothes when your occupation requires it!
