After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
Until now, the 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not only available for a &quot;humanitarian&quot; purpose, that is, individually and by name, at the request of a former victim or of his heirs.
The eleven states in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to search engines and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all the States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of the historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches &quot;particularly on the displacements of the prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced laborers&quot;, explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission. of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or the mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or of the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or subjected to compulsory labor countrymen and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way to your compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
&quot;There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,&quot; Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Search Center on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität in Berlin, had declared in 2006.
