New Russia-Ukraine Gas Fears
The growing dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk that it will affect the export of fuel to Western Europe by Russia.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, so every friction between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit fees.
An earlier dispute last year cut supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, the monopoly owner of gas, Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money Ukraine should pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom stated that it will charge Ukraine more, as Ukraine has agreed to pay an extra 50% in 2008 for gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say Ukraine could be paying 40% more for Gazprom imports.
&quot;It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transits for gas during the talks,&quot; Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
&quot;Changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments about the levels of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.&quot;
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supply with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations in Central Asia.
NHS &quot;shall test foreign workers&quot;
The Scottish NHS needs to monitor the criminal records of employees from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
Auditor General Robert Black&#39;s recommendation came after a foreign doctor was found to be linked to the attack on the Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea of the number of foreign staff it has.
However, his report pointed to other controls that are carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor general checked the number of foreign personnel recruited outside the European economic area, as a result of the attacks on the Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep outside the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Old Bailey via video conference in October, charged in connection with the alleged car bombings in the UK.
NHS expects to carry out pre-employment checks on candidates, to ensure that they meet the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Board of Health uses &quot;Disclosure Scotland&quot; to carry out criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Great Britain.
The auditor general&#39;s report recommends, among other measures, that boards should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
