Venus: Earth&#39;s twin brother.
Despite its atmosphere not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that had not been considered until now. The European probe &quot;Venus Express&quot; discovered lightning in the atmosphere and eddies at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
Researchers had suspected that lightning could exist on Venus for three decades.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, rays fall from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal &quot;Nature&quot;.
According to the famous Urey-Miller model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the building blocks of life.
It&#39;s not like that on Venus: if there were life there one day, it would have to be in one of the first stages of evolution, &quot;explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500 ° C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
&quot;Possibly Venus is an &#39;evil&#39; twin to Earth, but it&#39;s still a twin,&quot; Russell said.
The main objective of the &quot;Venus Express&quot; mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in its mass and size, has evolved so differently.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for research on this planet, the launch of &quot;Venus-Express&quot; in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest research results that will be presented in many &quot;Nature&quot; articles, in the opinion of the researchers, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
&quot;This also shows that neighboring planets have more common characteristics with Earth than we had expected,&quot; reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers discovered a faster-spinning vortex formed by clouds in the south polar region as well.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of the wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute for Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has a mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet, also called the morning star or evening star, orbits the Sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not closely resemble Earth, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had agglomerated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had turned into carbon stones, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
