They are not the wooden boxes.
Whoever relates the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Or if?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that hangs over Warhol&#39;s list of works.
Most of the ninety-four Gloss-Box &quot;types&quot; on this list are bogus.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper &quot;Expressen&quot; cast doubt on the authenticity of Andy Warhol&#39;s 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the Moderna Museet in Stockholm conducted internal investigations and reached disappointing conclusions: the six &quot;Brillo-Boxes &quot;, which the ex-director of the Pontus Hultén museum gave to the Moderna Museet museum, are false, and almost a hundred of the others of&quot; Stockholm type &quot;, which are in circulation in the international art market, also turn out.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first &quot;Brillo-Boxes&quot; in New York, he painted the wooden boxes red, blue and white, with the same sample that had &quot;Brillo&quot; soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his works in 1968 at the Moderna Museet hundreds of cardboard boxes were exhibited. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expense), but were brought directly from the &quot;Brillo&quot; cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but specimens (which were only a few objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed some wooden Brillo-boxes to be produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Modern Museet.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered art and auction history as originals of the &quot;Stockholm-type&quot; &quot;Brillo-Boxes&quot; authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions some of them were bought for more than $ 100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him were produced and exhibited.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in Saint Petersburg.
At this time Warhol had already died for 3 years.
Lars Byström, the chief curator of the Moderna Museet, investigated six Museum-owned Brillo-Boxes and also three privately owned Swedish that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. Their tight silvers were first printed and ground and then painted in oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the copies from the year 1990 shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed plates. Also, it is not about oil painting, but about acrylic painting.
&quot;These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes&quot;, says Lars Nittve, the director of the museum Moderna Museet and adds that if The Commission of Authentication &quot;Andy Warhol Art&quot; in New York he will not come to any conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify these six boxes as the copies / exhibits &quot;.
Already in July, the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these &quot;serious accusations&quot; in that they are boxes of soap powder.
But from that moment there everything remained in absolute silence.
